    role:"Nuclear physicists · uranium enrichment · strategic elimination",
    type:"death",badge:"☠ Confirmed State Operations",
    affiliations:["univ-tehran"],
    summary:"Between 2007 and 2020, at least six Iranian nuclear scientists were killed in operations widely attributed to Israeli intelligence (Mossad) with possible US coordination. These are not conspiracy theory. They are confirmed, documented, and publicly acknowledged, in some cases by the perpetrating governments, as the deliberate elimination of strategic scientific personnel. They represent the clearest available historical evidence that scientists working in consequential technical fields are, in the cold logic of statecraft, targetted for elimination. This entry is a baseline for the entire timeline: before asking whether the modern cluster represents deliberate targeting, note that deliberate targeting of scientists is an established practice of statecraft with a well-documented recent precedent.",
    sections:[{heading:"The documented cases",body:[
    "Ardeshir Hosseinpour, a nuclear engineer at the Isfahan uranium conversion facility, died under disputed circumstances in January 2007. Iranian authorities attributed his death to gas poisoning; Western intelligence analysts described it as the opening of a targeted operations campaign.",
    "Masoud Ali-Mohammadi, a particle physics professor at the University of Tehran, was killed on January 12, 2010, by a remote-controlled bomb attached to a motorcycle parked outside his home.",
    "Majid Shahriari, a nuclear engineer directly involved in Iran's centrifuge programme, was killed on November 29, 2010 in a coordinated attack: a motorcyclist attached a magnetic bomb to his moving car during morning traffic in Tehran. The same morning, Fereydoon Abbasi-Davani, later head of the Atomic Energy Organisation of Iran, survived a near-identical simultaneous attack.",
    "Darioush Rezaeinejad, an electronics engineer linked to high-voltage switches used in nuclear detonators, was shot outside his home in Tehran in July 2011.",
    "Mostafa Ahmadi Roshan, a chemistry expert and deputy director at the Natanz uranium enrichment facility, was killed by a magnetic bomb placed on his car during morning traffic on January 11, 2012.",
    "Mohsen Fakhrizadeh, described by the IAEA as the architect of Iran's covert nuclear weapons programme, a brigadier general in the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps, was killed on November 27, 2020 near Absard, east of Tehran. The operation used a remote-controlled machine gun mounted on a pickup truck, operated via satellite link with facial recognition targeting software. No personnel were physically present at the scene. This is what state-level targeted killing of scientists looks like in the 21st century, and it is documented in detail by every major international news organisation."
    ]},{heading:"Why this entry belongs on this timeline",body:[
    "The Iranian cases are included not because they have any direct connection to free energy research or the modern aerospace/nuclear cluster documented later in this timeline, but because they resolve an epistemological question: is deliberate targeted killing of scientists for strategic reasons something that actually happens, or is it conspiracy theory? The answer is that it happens. It is documented. It has been confirmed, in some cases by Western intelligence officials speaking on background and in others by the operational details of the attacks themselves. The lesson is not that the same forces are responsible for anything else on this timeline. The lesson is that the pattern should not be dismissed as impossible, because it is not impossible. It has happened repeatedly in the recent past."
    ]}],
    off:["All six assassinations are confirmed by international media reporting and forensic reconstruction of the attacks. No government has officially confirmed responsibility; both the United States and Israel maintain a policy of neither confirming nor denying specific covert operations. The Fakhrizadeh operation in particular was described in granular technical detail in international reporting, suggesting access to operational briefings. The systematic nature of the targeting, centrifuge specialists, weapons theorists, conversion facility engineers, warhead design architects, is not disputed."],
    links:[["Wikipedia, Assassination of Iranian nuclear scientists","https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assassination_of_Iranian_nuclear_scientists"],["BBC, Fakhrizadeh killing (Nov 2020)","https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-55101253"]],
